LOAD
  Move a commodity from a harbor sector onto a ship, or put a plane
  aboard a carrier or missile sub.

SYNTAX
  load <commodity> <ship-spec> <amount>
  load plane <ship-spec> <plane-spec>

DESCRIPTION
  COMMODITIES: transfers goods from a harbor sector into a ship's
  hold.  The ship must be located in a harbor sector (type 'h') that
  you own, and the harbor must be at least 2% efficient.

  <commodity>  - single letter: f=food c=civ m=mil l=lcm etc.
  <ship-spec>  - ship uid, range (0-5), or * for all matching ships
  <amount>     - how many units to load

  The ship takes up to <amount> from whatever the harbor has.  If
  the harbor has fewer than <amount>, it loads what it can.

  PLANES: 'load plane' puts a plane aboard a ship instead — no harbor
  needed, just that the plane and ship are currently at the same
  sector (open sea is fine; fly the plane there first with 'fly').

  <ship-spec>   - ship uid, range, comma list, "*", "~" (unfleeted),
                  or a fleet letter (see 'info fleetadd')
  <plane-spec>  - same forms as 'fly'/'recon' accept

  Only plane types flagged LIGHT, XLIGHT, HELO, or MISSILE can go
  aboard a ship at all (use 'show plane' to check a type's flags —
  most bombers/fighters/spy planes are land-based only). Within that,
  each ship type has separate capacity for regular (LIGHT) planes,
  extra-light planes, and choppers, plus an overall ceiling; missile
  planes (Harpoon, Sea Sparrow, Trident) count against the ceiling
  too, but need the ship flagged either CARRIER *or* MISSILE.

  This is the only way to get a plane onto a MISSILE-flagged ship
  (missile sub, nuc missile sub) — those never show up as an option
  when just flying to a carrier's sector (see 'info fly'), since that
  only offers CARRIER-flagged ships.  Build the missile at an airfield
  like any other plane (missiles have no separate harbor-build rule),
  fly it to the sub's sector, then 'load plane' it aboard.

  Regular carriers accept plane loading this way too — 'fly' straight
  onto a carrier's sector also works and is usually more convenient,
  but 'load plane' is the fallback if you need explicit control (e.g.
  a specific carrier among several at the same sector).

  Use 'info ship'/'show ship' to find ship uids and types.
  Use 'info unload' to take a commodity or plane back off.

EXAMPLE
  load food 0 500           load 500 food onto ship 0
  load civ 1 200            load 200 civilians onto ship 1
  load lcm * 50             load up to 50 LCM onto each ship in harbor
  load plane 14 5           load plane 5 onto ship 14 (same sector)
  load plane 19 20-25       load planes 20-25 onto ship 19 (a missile
                            sub, say — only planes flagged MISSILE or
                            otherwise carrier-eligible actually fit)

